      <reaction compartment="compartment_20699" fast="false" id="reaction_170844" metaid="metaid_131" name="Latent TGF-beta-1 is cleaved by FURIN" reversible="false">
        <notes>
          <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">In the Golgi apparatus, TGF-beta-1 (TGFB1) is activated by furin protease cleavage of the N-terminal pro-peptide portion. This leads to the formation of the N-terminal disulphide-linked dimeric pro-peptides, also known as latency-associated proteins (LAPs) and the C-terminal mature disulphide-linked dimeric TGF-beta-1 (Dubois et al. 1995, Dubois et al. 2001, Leitlein et al. 2001). However, the N- and C-terminal polypeptides do not physically separate. Rather they stay in one complex. In addition, the LAP forms disulphide links with separate secreted proteins, the Latent TGF-beta binding proteins (LTBPs). LTBPs-linked to LAP and the non-covalently linked mature TGF-beta-1 remain together and form the large latent complex (LLC) (Annes et al. 2003).</p>
        </notes>
        <annotation>
          <rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:vCard="http://www.w3.org/2001/vcard-rdf/3.0#" xmlns:dcterms="http://purl.org/dc/terms/" xmlns:bqbiol="http://biomodels.net/biology-qualifiers/">
